data(tetragonula)

dis <- tai$distmat
mdscaling <- mds(as.matrix(dis))
plot(mdscaling$conf)

mdscaling$stress    
## [1] 0.2619208
# hierarchical methods (compl linkage, single linkage, avg linkage)
complink <- hclust(as.dist(dis), method = "complete")
plot(complink, labels = F, main = "Complete linkage", xlab = "")

# hierarchical methods (compl linkage, single linkage, avg linkage)
singlink <- hclust(as.dist(dis), method = "single")
plot(singlink, labels = F, main = "Single linkage", xlab = "")

# hierarchical methods (compl linkage, single linkage, avg linkage)
avglink <- hclust(as.dist(dis), method = "average")
plot(avglink, labels = F, main = "Average linkage", xlab = "")

Here I decided to use the average linkage method since it’s a compromise between separation(single linkage) and homogeneity between clusters (complete linkage). Since I have small knowledge about genetic data and how to cluster it, the chosen method is the one which is less “extreme”. The choice of k=6 allows to have clusters with a reasonable number of observations. Plus, I did not opt for a smaller k since the following aggregations happened at too big values of height.

Point b

#kmeans on mds values 
library(cluster)

gapnc <- function(data,FUNcluster=kmeans, K.max=10, B = 100, d.power = 2, spaceH0 ="scaledPCA", method ="globalSEmax", SE.factor = 2,...)
{
gap1 <- clusGap(data,kmeans,K.max, B, d.power,spaceH0,...) 
nc <- maxSE(gap1$Tab[,3],gap1$Tab[,4],method, SE.factor) 
kmopt <- kmeans(data,nc,...) 
out <- list() 
out$gapout <- gap1 
out$nc <- nc 
out$kmopt <- kmopt 
out
}

gap_output <- gapnc(mdscaling$conf, K.max = 10, nstart=100, SE.factor = 2)
mdsdata <- as.data.frame(mdscaling$conf)
mdsdata$cl <- gap_output$kmopt$cluster
plot(mdsdata[,1:2],col=mdsdata$cl,pch=clusym[mdsdata$cl])

#ward method on mds values
eucldist <- dist(mdsdata[,1:2], method = "euclidean")
ward <-  hclust(dist(eucldist),method="ward.D2")
plot(ward, labels=FALSE, xlab = "mds data")

# 4 seems to be a reasonable n°of clusters
ward4 <- cutree(ward, k=4)
mdsdata$cl <- ward4
plot(mdsdata[,1:2],col=mdsdata$cl,pch=clusym[mdsdata$cl])

#mixture models
library(mclust)
mixtmdsdata <- Mclust(mdsdata[,1:2],G=1:8)
summary(mixtmdsdata)    #VVE with 7 components is chosen
## ---------------------------------------------------- 
## Gaussian finite mixture model fitted by EM algorithm 
## ---------------------------------------------------- 
## 
## Mclust VVE (ellipsoidal, equal orientation) model with 7 components: 
##

##        11.20011 236 35 -168.8339 -171.0657
## 
## Clustering table:
##  1  2  3  4  5  6  7 
## 35 23 16 20 15 63 64
summary(mixtmdsdata$BIC) 
## Best BIC values:
##              VVE,7       VVV,7       VVE,8
## BIC      -168.8339 -171.559535 -176.686823
## BIC diff    0.0000   -2.725638   -7.852926
mdsdata$cl <- mixtmdsdata$classification
plot(mdsdata[,1:2],col=mdsdata$cl,pch=clusym[mdsdata$cl])

The main advantage of this approach is that our data are transformed in euclidean data: working on euclidean distances is simpler for many applications and for interpretation. The main drawback is the loss of information: this is quantified by the quantity “stress” computed above, and we could say that, in applying multidim.scaling to 2 dimensions, we lose a big amount of information.
As a consequence, I don’t think that this approaches are ultimately better, because we perform a clustering method on data that are not the original ones, and we don’t see the whole “picture” in this way, in particular on only 2 dimensions. I would prefere the use of MDS in 2 dimensions only for graphical and visualization purposes.
In this task, Multidimensional Scaling in only 2 dimensions loses a remarkable quantity of information (26%). For this reason, I would say that a multidim.scaling in 3 or more dimensional would be better, since we would lose less information before applying a clustering method. However, using 3 dimensions, it would be impossible to produce a scatterplot and visualize correctly the clusters.

Among these three, I would choose the Ward method on scaled data. Since we are looking at medical data, I would like to have a small number of cluster and to have a sort of separation between them. Plus, with unscaled data some variables with higher size would have more importance in the computation of the distances: this could be bad, at least in this field (we are not medical experts). The Gaussian mixture is able to find another clustering pattern in the data, but, as I said before, any kind of overlapping in my opinion seems undesirable.

Exercise 3

Exercise 4

Complete linkage clustering: what is the best combination of standardization and distance construction?

These plot show the value of the Adjusted Rand Index for clusterings obtained from different combinations of standardization method and

  1. Base setup: the best values of ARI are achieved by L1 distance; there isn’t a standardization method that’s significantly better than others.
  2. 0.99 noise setup: Overall, L1 performs slightly better than other distances. The range standardization and NO standardization produce the best results.
  3. 0.1 noise setup: L1 with var standardization, range standardization and boxplot tranformation achieve an ARI of 1. That means that the Manhattan distance (after such standardizations) is able to reproduce the true clustering
  4. 0.5 noise setup: L1 with var, range or boxplot standardization reach a value near 1.
  5. 0.9 noise setup: L1 with var, range or boxplot transformation (the latter is slightly better than the other two)

Conclusions: The L1 distance produces the best values of ARI in all the experiments. Overall, the standardization that makes possible to reproduce better the true clustering is the Range one. Also var and boxplot transformations give good performances, but when there’s a lot of noise the range std manage to produce good values of ARI.

PAM vs Complete linkage clustering

  1. Partitioning around medoids gives better results for high exponents of Minkovski distances (except L=2), while L1 performs quite well for both the clusterings.
  2. Very similar results (slightly better for complete linkage)
  3. PAM is way better for almost all exponents of Minkovski (except L=2 that always produces an ARI of 0)
  4. PAM is more suitable for higher exponents (as before, L2 does not a good job in both types of clustering)
  5. Similar results , for three types of STD L1 performs better in complete linkage clustering.

Conclusions: Partitioning around medoids performs better for these data when the proportion of “noise” variables is quite low (0, 0.1 and 0.5), since it produces higher positive values of ARI when we use a Minkovski distance with an exponent greater than 2. L1 and L2 aren’t really affected by the choice between PAM and complete linkage (L1 is very good in finding the true clustering, L2 is very bad).
When we have a lot of variables contamined with outliers and strongly varying within-class variation (noise = 0.9 or 0.99), the results are quite similar, while complete linkage is slighty better in some situations.
